<DOC><DOCNO> AP890907-0302 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 2341EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Armco     09-07 0184</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Armco,0191</SECOND><HEAD>Armco Agreement Ratified</HEAD><DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Members of the United Steelworkers unionratified a new four-year agreement with Armco Inc., the union saidThursday.   The agreement covers 4,700 Armco workers at plants in Ashland,Ky., Kansas City, Mo., and Baltimore, Md. It was approved by a mailballot vote of 3,011 to 685, the union said.   ``This is an outstanding agreement consistent with the patternestablished at other major steel producers that restores pastsacrifices, assures future economic improvements and develops newprograms for training,'' said Jim Bowen, chairman of the USWbargaining committee.   Highlights of the agreement, which runs through July 31, 1993,include a $500 signing bonus, a profit-sharing plan and immediaterestoration of past wage sacrifices that averaged $1 an hour at theBaltimore and Kansas City plants.   The agreement also features wage increases at Baltimore andKansas City averaging 35 cents an hour on Aug. 1, 1991, and 40 centsan hour a year later. Ashland workers will receive average increasesof $1 an hour on Jan. 1, 1991, and 25 cents each of the followingyears.</TEXT></DOC>